{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657270"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:26:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:26:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19169"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19169"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.06,0.13,0.47,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11903"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81747"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11903"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19169"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67038"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27887"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28128"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81747"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA diagnostic test correctly identifies 85 out of 100 patients who have a disease. Of the patients with the disease, 15 receive a negative test result.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statistical measures is being described?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Negative predictive value","Positive likelihood ratio","Specificity","Sensitivity","Positive predictive value"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes \u003Cstrong\u003Esensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the ability of a test to correctly identify those who have the disease (true positive rate). It is calculated as: True Positives \u00f7 (True Positives + False Negatives) = 85 \u00f7 (85 + 15) = 85%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other measures are different:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENegative predictive value\u003C/strong\u003E is the probability that subjects with a negative test truly do not have the disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive likelihood ratio\u003C/strong\u003E is the ratio of true positive rate to false positive rate (sensitivity divided by 1-specificity)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpecificity\u003C/strong\u003E measures the proportion of true negatives correctly identified (those without disease who test negative)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositive predictive value\u003C/strong\u003E is the probability that subjects with a positive test truly have the disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, we are given that 85 patients were correctly identified out of 100 patients who had the disease, with 15 false negatives. This directly describes sensitivity without needing any other information about test performance in disease-free individuals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sensitivity measures the proportion of true positive cases correctly identified by a test.","Sensitivity is also known as the true positive rate or recall.","Sensitivity is calculated by dividing true positives by the sum of true positives and false negatives."],"references":["Shreffler et al. Diagnostic Testing Accuracy: Sensitivity, Specificity, Predictive Values and Likelihood Ratios. StatPearls. 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557491/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67038"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19169"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67038","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67038"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T20:50:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-29T15:23:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11903"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81747"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/16"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4947"},"attributes":{"